    "language": "english",
    "review": "Explore the sea, manage your restaurant, defeat small fish and big fish, help people, collect things.\nIt's a mixture of a exploration game with a restaurant management game, with a RPG game and some others.\n\n[b] One of the things I have to highlight the most is that you can tell this game was made with a lot of love. Nothing was rushed or scuffed. The details (and exaggerated cutscenes) are incredible. Hello, game companies, learn from this one [/b]\n\n[h3] Pros [/h3]\n- Great controls\n- Combat is pretty good, though I wish melee was more viable somehow\n- Awesome progression, you never stop unlocking new stuff until the very end of the game (lots of games don't get progression as good as this one)\n- Upgrades to your stuff actually feel satisfying (also another thing games don't usually get it right)\n- There is always stuff happening, this makes the game not feel boring at any point. There is A LOT of content\n- Main quest line and all side quests length are just right, doesn't feel like a short game nor a very long one (took me 42 hours for main quests, side quests and a few optional things with maybe a few hours being afk). I optimized all objectives during my dives but it could have easily have taken 50% more time to finish everything if I took my time\n- Visual clarity, it's easy to differentiate everything in the sea, except for maybe nettable creatures\n- Great soundtrack\n- Great graphics (for a 2D semi pixelated game)\n- Achievements are not a super pain to get, though I'll most likely not aim for 100%\n- Fun and very elaborated minigames, honestly I'd play some of these on my phone if I could\n- The game didn't feel grindy at any point, I never really had to do dives for grinding resources though I tried to min max and optimize my dives as much as I could\n\n[h3] Neutral [/h3]\n- Story is ok, nothing spectacular, pretty wholesome I'd say\n- [spoiler] Beluga in Sea People city has no reason to be paid, though the currency used shouldn't be a concern after the very beginning [/spoiler]. Not a big deal but I don't understand the reasoning here, especially because you can afford a slightly cheaper price in certain areas\n- I wish some puzzles were difficult, they were all very easy and some of them were even impossible to get it wrong\n- At some point, we have plenty of things to manage if we want to make use of everything, it feels like chores if you do it too much. I completed the game about the same time I was getting tired of doing all the stuff, so it's ok. And no, [spoiler] I'm not paying that much money to have the guy take care of my farm, it's just not worth it until I'm making like 10k+ profit every day and have no other use for money [/spoiler]. I'd honestly play more to farm at least the achievements but managing everything kinda threw me off\n- The game has a more casual vibe, it doesn't really feel hard or challenging at any point\n\n[h3] Cons [/h3]\n- Lack of QoL in restaurant management. I don't know how many plates I served each night to have some sort of idea of how much food should be in the menu. I'd love to min max without any waste of materials I'll have to grind back if needed\n- Lack of QoL in [spoiler] fish tanks [/spoiler], let me preset things to either [spoiler] sell or send to kitchen [/spoiler] automatically so I don't have to [spoiler] visit the tank [/spoiler] every day and have one more thing to manage every day\n- [spoiler] Additional branch [/spoiler] felt unnecessary and meaningless. I could have missed something because I finished the game right when I unlocked it, so it didn't actually [spoiler] \n worked a single day [/spoiler] \n- Workers progression is not as good as all the other things, they should probably have half the levels that they have (from 20 cap to 10)\n- The game never seemed to inform me what is Procure and Appeal in workers stats. I assumed Procure is the ability to find items when you dispatch them? But I'm not sure\n- I never felt like I needed all the different weapons the game have to offer, it feels like I only need a high DPS weapon and one weapon to get Rank 3 fishes which is not even a necessity tbh. I could see uses for the options of weapons but it never felt that one option was better than another in any situation, it always came down to dealing a lot of damage with a good proportion of damage to bullets ratio or just the ability to capture fish without killing them. No use for AoE weapons, no real use for [spoiler] poison, fire, lightning, [/spoiler] etc",
